[Student "S"]
{When partner opens 1NT, interference can easily gum up your smooth bidding sequences. Playing the lebensohl convention, your 3\H bid shows a 5-card suit and is forcing to game.

It doesn't always work out so well, but here partner had an easy 4\H bid.

East plays 4\H. South leads the \ST.

Whatever you play, North takes the \S A K J and then plays a small \C. South started with just one \S.

Loser List: \S = 3 : \H = ? : \D = 0 : \C = 0 :: Total = ?

Don't let that Question Mark by the \H losers mislead you - if you are going to make this contract you cannot lose a \H trick at all! Is there any hope? 

The odds aren't good, but you actually have <b>TWO</b> possibilities for success. If South holds the singleton \HK, you can play a small \H to dummy's \HA, dropping the \HK, then finesse North out of his \HJ. Or, if North holds the singleton \HJ you can play your \HQ, finessing South for the \HK and at the same time smothering North's \HJ.

Which basket will you put your eggs into? 

The answer is simple Bridge math! North started with 6 \Ss leaving him 7 cards outside the \S suit. South started with just 1 \S, leaving him with 12 cards outside the \S suit. Obviously North is much more likely to have a singleton \H than South.

So you win the \CA in your hand, play the \HQ and let it ride if South does not cover.

Then you  

Ahh, success.

But to tell the truth, the Bridge math wasn't really complete. Distribution-wise it was just fine, but there is also the question of strength.

The fact that North overcalled makes it more likely that he holds more high cards than South, and this skews the odds toward North holding the \HK.

But think about it. If North does in fact hold the singleton \HK, and if you cleverly drop it by playing dummy's \HA it won't help you. You will then have to lose a trick to South's \HJ.}
[Play "W"]ST

